The proof is remarkably simple! Let's explain why:

When we apply `simp [kerLift]`, Lean unfolds the definition of `kerLift`. The definition of `kerLift` is `Ideal.Quotient.lift (ker f) f`. So, applying this to `Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) x` means we compute `f (Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) x)`.

But `Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) x` is the equivalence class of `x` modulo `ker f`. By the definition of the quotient, two elements `x, y` are equivalent if `x - y ∈ I`. Since `x - x = 0 ∈ I` (because `f x = 0` implies `x ∈ I`), we have `x ≡ x (mod I)`. Therefore, `Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) x` is the equivalence class containing `x`.

When we apply `f` to this equivalence class, we get `f x`.

The `simp` tactic is powerful enough to handle these definitions and simplifications automatically. It knows how to compute `f (Ideal.Quotient.mk (ker f) x)` and simplify it to `f x`.

So, the complete proof is just `simp [kerLift]`.

The final answer is $ \boxed{f x} $, which is exactly what the theorem states.
